The denotational semantics is given in \cref{fig:den-sem1}.
\begin{itemize}
\item We have one semantic function (here $\semfun{E}$ and $\semfun{V}$) for each syntactic
  non terminal (here $e$ and $v$ respectively.)
\item Each function has one equation for each form of the construct.
\item Both functions take an environment $\rho$ that maps in-scope identifiers to
  a \emph{single} value; see the definition $\Env = Ident \rightarrow \Value$.
\item The value function $\semfun{V}$ returns a \emph{single value} $\Value$, while
  the expression function $\semfun{E}$ returns a \emph{collection of values} $\mtype$ (\cref{sec:collection}).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{What is a ``collection of values''?} \label{sec:collection}

The semantics is parameterised over the meaning of a ``collection of values $\mtype$''.
To a first approximation, think of $\mtype$ a (possibly infinite) set of values $\Value$,
with union, intersection etc having their ordinary meaning.

Our first interpretation,
given in \Cref{fig:set-sem}, is a little more refined: $\mtype$ includes $\bot$ and $\wrong$ as
well as a set of values.  Our second interpretation is given in \Cref{fig:labelled-sem}, and
discussed in \Cref{sec:order-sensitive}.

\subsection{The equations}

The equations themselves, in \cref{fig:den-sem1}
are beautifully simple and compositional, as a denotational semantics should be.

The equations for $\semfun{V}$ are mostly self-explanatory, but an equation like $\semapp{V}{|k|}{\rho} = k$ needs some
explanation: the $k$ on the left hand side (e.g. ``|3|'') is a piece of \emph{syntax}, but the $k$ on the right is the corresponding
element of the \emph{semantic world of values} $\Value$ (e.g. $3$). As is conventional, albeit a bit confusing,
we use the same $k$ for both.  Same for $op$, where the semantic equivalent is the corresponding mathematical function.

The equations for $\semfun{E}$ are more interesting.
\begin{itemize}
\item Values $\semapp{E}{|v|}{\rho}$: compute the single value for |v|, and return a singleton set of results.
The auxiliary function $\munit$ is defined at the bottom of \cref{fig:den-sem1}.
\item Choice $\semapp{E}{|e_1 choice e_2|}{\rho}$: take the union (written $\munion$) of the values
  returned by |e_1| and |e_2| respectively.  For bags this union operator is just bag union (\Cref{fig:set-sem}).
\item Unification $\semapp{E}{|e_1 choice e_2|}{\rho}$: take the \emph{intersection} of the
  values returned by |e_1| and |e_2| respectively. For bags, this ``intersection'' operator $\mintersect$
  is defined in \cref{fig:set-sem}. In this definition, the equality is mathematical equality of functions;
  which we can't implement for functions; see \Cref{sec:unification-and-equality}.
\item Sequencing $\semapp{E}{|e_1 ; e_2|}{\rho}$. Again we use an auxiliary function $\msemi$ to combine
  the meanings of |e_1| and |e_2|. For bags, the function $\msemi$ (\cref{fig:set-sem} again)
  uses a bag comprehension.  Again it does a cartesian product, but without the equality constraint of $\mintersect$.
\item Function application $\semapp{E}{|apply1N v_1 v_2|}{\rho}$ is easy, because $\semfun{V}$ returns a single value: just apply
  the meaning of the function to the meaning of the argument.  The $\apply$ function is defined in \Cref{fig:den-sem1}.
\item The semantics of |(one e)| simply applies the semantic function $\mone : \mtype \rightarrow \mtype$ to the
  collection of values returned by |e|.  If |e| returns no values, so does |(one e)|; but if |e| returns one or more values,
  |(one e)| returns the first.  Of course that begs the question of what ``the first'' means -- for bags
  it would be non-deterministic. We will fix this problem in \Cref{sec:order-sensitive}, but for now we simply ignore it.
\item The semantics of |(all e)| is similar, but it always returns a singleton collection
  (hence the $\munit$ in the semantics of |all|) whose
  element is a (possibly-empty) tuple that contains all the values in the collection returned by |e|.
\end{itemize}
The fact that unification ``|=|'' maps onto intersection, and choice ``|choice|'' onto union, is
very satisfying.

\subsection{Functions}

How are functions handled?
Values include lambdas, so this semantics says that a lambda evaluates to a singleton
collection, whose only element is a function value. But that function value has
type $\Value \rightarrow \mtype$; that is, it is a function that takes a single
value and returns a \emph{collection} of values.  This is not TimLambda, but it's simple and well-understood.

% \subsection{Hastype}
% 
% The meaning of |(hastype e_1 e_2)| is the meaning of |e_1|, provided the meaning
%  of |(apply1N e_1 e_2)| has the same meaning.  If not, the expression has meaning $\wrong$.
%  The ``has the same meaning'' test takes places in the mathematical world, so it means
%  ``the same in all contexts''.  It follows that |(hastype e_1 e_2)| should yield $\wrong$ if $e_1$ can differ
%  from |(apply1N e_1 e_2)| \emph{in any context}.  If not (and the verifier can prove this) we can
%  simply replace |(hastype e_1 e_2)| by |e_1|.

\subsection{Existentials} \label{sec:unification-and-equality}

The big excitement is the treatment of |defKW|. We must extend $\rho$, but what should we bind |x| to?  (Compare the
equation for $\semapp{V}{|lam x e|}{}$, where we have a value $w$ to hand.)
Our answer is simple: \emph{try all possible values, and union the results}:
$$
\semapp{E}{|def x e|}{\rho} \; = \; \bigcup_{w \in \Value}\, \semapp{E}{e}{(\extendrho{\rho}{x \mapsto w})}
$$
That $\bigcup_{w \in \Value}$ means: enumerate all values in $w \in \Value$, in some arbitrary order,
and for each: bind $x$ to $w$, find the semantics of $e$ for that value of $x$, namely
$\semapp{E}{e}{(\extendrho{\rho}{x \mapsto w})}$, and take the union
(in the sense of $\munion$) of the results.

Of course we can't possibly implement it like this, but it makes a great specification.
For example |def x (x=3)| tries all possible values for |x|, but only one of them succeeds, namely |3|, so
the semantics is a singleton set $[3]$.

\subsection{The denotational semantics is un-implementable}

This semantics is nice and simple, but we definitely can't implement it!  Consider
$$
|def x ((square x - x - 6) = 0; x|
$$
The semantics will iterate over all possible values for |x|, returning all those that satisfy the equality;
including $3$, for example. But unless our implementation can guarantee to solve quadratic equations,
we can't expect it to return 3.  Instead it'll get stuck.

Another way in which the implementation might get stuck is through unifying functions:
$$
|(lam x (x+x)) = (lam y (y * 2))|
\quad \text{or even} \quad
|(lam x (x+1)) = (lam y (y+1))|
$$
But not all unification-over-functions is ruled out.  We do expect the implementation to succeed with
$$
|def f (((lam x (x+1)) = f); apply1N f 3)|
$$
Here the |defKW| will iterate over all values of |f|, and the equality will pick out the (unique) iteration
in which |f| is bound to the incrementing function.

So our touchstone must be:
\begin{itemize}
\item If the implementation returns a value at all, it must be the value given by the semantics.
\item Ideally, the verifier will guarantee that the implementation does not get stuck, or go $\wrong$.
\end{itemize}

This reminded Koen of something that Esterelle does.  (Details, Koen?)

\subsection{Getting $\wrong$ right}

Getting $\wrong$ right is a bit tricky.


\begin{itemize}
\item What is the value of |(3 = emptytup)|?  The intersection semantics would say $\mempty$, the empty collection
  of results, but we might want to say $\wrong$.
\item Should $\wrong$ be an element of $\Value$ or of $\mtype$?  We probably want |(one (3 `choice` wrong)|
  to return a $\munit(3)$ rather then $\wrong$?
\item What about |apply1 fst (tup (3,wrong))|?  Is that wrong or 3?
\end{itemize}

There is probably more than one possible choice here.


