\simon{From here on the presentation becomes much more flaky and speculative.}

This section describes micro-lambdas.  See figure \ref{fig:micro-syntax} for syntax,
and \Cref{fig:micro-desugar} for some desugaring rules.

\subsection{Informal semantics, and examples}

\begin{itemize}
\item The denotation of an expression is a set of (tagged) values.
\item A micro-lambda has the syntax |mlam v_1 v_2|.  It stands for the set of all
  functions that map the input |v_1| to the output |v_2|, but is otherwise unspecified.
  No variables get bound in this construct! For example |mlam x x| has two (bound) occurrences of |x|,
  not (as would normally be the case) a binding site and a bound occurrence.
% \item There is a universal quantifier, |univ x e|.  It is the intersection of all
%  denotations of |e_2| as |x| ranges over all values.  The |x| may not occur in |e_1|.
\item The existential quantifier has a domain, |quantE x e_1 e_2|, where |x| will range over
 the values in the denotation of |e_1|.  The |x| may not occur in |e_1|.
\item There is a universal quantifier, |quantA x e_1 e_2|.  It is the intersection of all
 denotations of |e_2| as |x| ranges of the denotation of |e_1|.  The |x| may not occur in |e_1|.
\item The expression |domain e| is the set of functions that are unspecified when the argument is
  in the denotation of |e|, and fails when it is not.
\item Note that semicolon ``|;|'' is desugared away into $\exists$.
  We could alternatively have the old (unbounded) $\exists$ and and ``|;|'', by desugaring
  |(quantE x e_1 e_2)| to |def x (x=e_1; e2)|.  Then we also would not need |ANY| in |e|.  This acutally
  seems nicer (more orthogonal).
\end{itemize}

\lennart{The propagation of labels when there are quantifiers needs some thought.}

Some examples:
\begin{itemize}
  \item |mlam 0 1| denotes the set of all functions |f| that map |0| to |1|,
  but is otherwise unspecified. For example, this set includes |lam x (x+1)| and |lam x 1| and |lam x (x*200 + 1)|.

  \item |mlam 0 1 = mlam 1 0| is a (set of) function that maps 0 to 1
    and 1 to 0, but otherwise unspecified.  This looks pretty odd!  But remember that equality |=| takes the \emph{intersection} of the denotations of its arguments.

  \item |mlam 0 1 = mlam 1 0 = domain(0 `choice` 1)| is a function
    that maps 0 to 1, 1 to 0, and fails for all other inputs.  The ``fail everywhere else'' part is
    done by the |domain|.

  \item The source expression |(x : int) => x+1| is a (set of) all functions that compute the successor for an integer argument; and have unspecified behaviour for non-integer arguments.
    It desugars to |quantA x (:int) (quantE y ((x+1)) (mlam x y))|.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Denotational semantics}

The denotational semantics is in \Cref{fig:micro-den-sem}.

\begin{itemize}
\item The function part of the domain of values $\Value$ is $\Value
  \rightarrow \mtyped$; that is the function returns 0 or 1 value;
  that is, it is (isomorphic to) a \emph{partial function}.  We aren't
  quite sure about this.  Would $\Value \rightarrow \Value$ work?

\item Do $\bot$ and $\wrong$ live in $\mtype$ as well as $\Value$?  Or would it
  be $\munit(\wrong)$?
\end{itemize}

