This section dicusses TimLambda.

\subsection{Overview}

The syntax is given in \Cref{fig:tim-syntax}.

\begin{itemize}
\item In the TimLambda semantics the meaning of $\mtype$ is a set of values.
The necessary sequencing for choice is handle by labelling (as above).

\item A $\lambda$-expression has the following (complex) syntax
$$
|lam x (def (y_1 dots y_n) (where e_1 dot e_2))|
$$
Here |e_1| is called the \emph{domain expression} of the lambda, while |e_2| is called the \emph{range expression}.

\item The bound variables |x| and |y_1 dots y_n| scope over both |e_1| and |e_2|.
  The domain expression |e_1| can give values to the existential variables, |y_1 dots y_n|, typically
  derived from the value of the argument |x|.
  We will omit the existential quantifier when there are no |y_i|.

\item Note that, instead of being a value |v| yielding one value (as in \Cref{fig:syntax}),
  a lambda is an expression |e| yielding many values.

\item Informally |(lam x (def (y_1 dots y_n) (where e_1 dot e_2)))|
  stands for the set of all functions $f : \Value \rightarrow \mtyped$ (i.e. taking a single value to a single value or failing),
  such that for all arguments $w$ to the function,
  when |e_1| denotes a non-empty set then the result of the function $f(w)$ is an element of the denotation of |e_2|.

  \Cref{fig:tim-den-sem1} gives several attempts at formalising this idea.

\item Since the denotation of a $\lambda$-expression is a set of functions, it means that the denotation
  of a function application, $f(w)$, is also a set.  But if the function range is single valued, then all
  the functions in the set have the same result when the argument is in the domain.
  Thus, the set $f(w)$ is a singleton set if $w$ is in the domain.
  This means that the meaning of TimLambdas agree with regular lambdas for values in the domain.

\end{itemize}

