\subsection{Examples}

E.g., the source Verse function |0 eqgt 1| stands for the the TimLambda |lam x (where x = 0 dot 1)|.
The denotation of this is the set of all functions that when given |0| returns |1|.
This is an infinite set, among its members is the successor function and the constant 1 function.

The source Verse function |(x:int) eqgt x| stands for the the TimLambda |lam x (def y (where y = int(x) dot y))|.
The denotation of this is the set of all functions that when given an |int| returns that |int|.
This is an infinite set, among its members is the identity function and the |int| type test.

Figure \ref{fig:tim-example1} has a full example of the source Verse function |(x:succ) => x|,
where the denotation of |succ| is singleton
set with the function that is the successor for integer arguments, and that fails for other arguments
(i.e., it means exactly what you think it means).  I.e.,

$$
\semapp{E}{succ}{\rho} = \munits{\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
  \lambda x . \munits{x+1} & \text{if $x \in k$ } \\
  \lambda x . \varnothing & \text{otherwise}
\end{array}
\right. }
$$

Reading off the final result, we can see that the denotation is the set of all functions $\Value \rightarrow \mtyped$
such that if the argument is an integer the result is the singleton set with the successor of the argument.
If the argument is not an integer the function can do anything.

