\subsection{Labelled semantics for TimLambda}
See \Cref{fig:tim-labelled-sem}

\section{Functions}
Here is an alternative formulation of how function definitions are desugared.
A function definition of the form
$$
|apply1 f (def (x_1 xdots x_n) e_1) := e_2|
$$
is desugared as (glossing over the fact that we need a |defKW f| somewhere)
$$
|f == lam x (if (def (x_1 xdots x_n) (x == e_1)) then e_2 else def y y)|
$$
\Eg,
$$
|apply1 fac 0 := 1|
$$
is desugared as
$$
|fac == lam x (if (x == 0) then 1 else def y y)|
$$
The meaning of |fac|, according to the denotational semantics,
is the set of all functions that map |0| to |1| but otherwise can behave in any way.

To continue with factorial
$$
|apply1 fac (def n (n>0)) := n * apply1 fac (n - 1)|
$$
desugars to
$$
|fac == lam x (if (def n (x == (n>0))) then n * apply1 fac (n - 1) else def y y|
$$
simplifies to
$$
|fac == lam x (if (x>0)) then x * apply1 fac (x - 1) else def y y|
$$
and, denotationally, this is the set of function that behave
like factorial, except that the base case (when |x==0|) can be anything.
Putting these together
$$
\begin{array}{l}
|fac == lam x (if (x == 0) then 1 else def y y)| \\
|fac == lam x (if (x>0)) then x * apply1 fac (x - 1) else def y y|
\end{array}
$$
Since $=$ corresponds to set intersection the |fac| function is
now the set of functions that behave like factorial for non-negative integers,
but otherwise unconstrained.

So the denotation of, \eg, |one (apply1 fac 5)| is $\{120\}$, whereas
the denotation of |one (apply1 fac (-1))| is $\wrong$, since the set
of results of the application is not a singleton.

